statement.p:
The function \displaystyle f(x) = \frac{x}{x^2+3}
has a derivative f'(x) = \frac{3-x^2}{(x^2+3)^2}.
Describe the local extreme values of f(x).

image.latex-image:

\tikzset{%
}
\begin{tikzpicture}[x=1cm,y=1cm]
\draw[<->] (-3,0) -- (3,0) node[above right] {$f'(x)$} node[below right] {$x$};

\draw (0, -0.1) -- (0, 0.1) node[pos=0, below] {$0$} node[pos=1,above] {$0$};
\draw (-1.7, -0.1) -- (-1.7, 0.1) node[pos=0, below] {$-\sqrt{3}$} node[pos=1,above] {$0$};
\draw (1.7, -0.1) -- (1.7, 0.1) node[pos=0, below] {$\sqrt{3}$} node[pos=1,above] {$0$};
\node [above] at (-2.2,0) {$-$};
\node [above] at (0,0) {$+$};
\node [above] at (2.2,0) {$-$};
\end{tikzpicture}

\tikzset{%
}
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}
[ xmin=-8, xmax=8, ymin=-0.5, ymax=0.5,
axis lines=center ]
\addplot [domain=-8:8, samples=101] { x/(x^2+3) };
\addplot [only marks] coordinates {
    (-1.732, {-1.732/6}) (1.732, {1.732/6})
}
node [pos=0, below left] {$x=-\sqrt{3}$}
node [pos=1, above right] {$x=\sqrt{3}$};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

solution.p:
Regardless of which domain we use, we will need to find the local extreme values. Local extreme values are identified from sign analysis of f'(x). We find f'(x)=4(2x) - (3x^2) = 8x - 3x^2. Sign analysis begins by finding the roots, where f'(x)=0.
8x-3x^2 = 0 x(8-3x) = 0 x=0, \quad 8-3x=0 x=0, \quad x=\frac{8}{3}
Because f'(x) is continuous, the roots determine the test intervals: (-\infty,0), (0,\frac{8}{3}), and (\frac{8}{3},\infty). Testing one value of x from each interval in f'(x) = x(8-3x), we find the signs summarized on the following number line.

